# Available Sub-Agents

Lead types and their docs are listed in **docs/leads/**.

## Agent role reference

Quick-pick table — use this before deciding which agent to dispatch:

| Agent                            | Read/Write | Dispatched when                                                     | Output                                             |
| -------------------------------- | ---------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------- |
| **implementer**                  | read-write | Normal task execution from `tg next`                                | Code changes + `tg done` evidence                  |
| **reviewer** (PASS/FAIL mode)    | read-only  | After implementer completes a task                                  | `VERDICT: PASS` or `FAIL` with issues              |
| **reviewer** (research mode)     | read-only  | `/investigate` skill needs architectural research                   | Structured findings + suggested tasks              |
| **investigator** (hunter-killer) | read-write | `gate:full` fails at plan end                                       | `STATUS` report: root cause + fix applied          |
| **debugger**                     | read-write | Fix build/compilation errors; unclear root cause; single debug task | `tg done` with root-cause evidence                 |
| **fixer**                        | read-write | Implementer has failed twice on same task                           | `tg done` with fix evidence                        |
| **planner-analyst**              | read-only  | Before writing any plan                                             | Structured analysis for orchestrator               |
| **documenter**                   | read-write | Doc-only tasks (`agent: documenter` in plan)                        | Updated docs + `tg done`                           |
| **spec-reviewer**                | read-only  | Two-stage review: spec compliance check                             | `VERDICT: PASS` or `FAIL`                          |
| **quality-reviewer**             | read-only  | Two-stage review: code quality check                                | `VERDICT: PASS` or `FAIL`                          |
| **adversarial-security-reviewer** | read-only | Security / red-team review of change set                            | VERDICT: PASS / CONCERNS / FAIL + risks, severity  |
| **risk-preparedness-reviewer**   | read-only  | Change-level risk scorecard (deployment, ops, rollback)              | Scorecard + top mitigations                        |
| **factuality-traceability-reviewer** | read-only | Claims in code/docs vs reality; traceability                        | PASS / FAIL + specific inconsistencies            |
| **fairness-equity-auditor**      | read-only  | Task graph and process balance (plans, agents, runnable set)         | Structured report: skews, rebalances               |
| **rubric-driven-reviewer**      | read-only  | Multi-dimension rubric evaluation of change or plan                  | Per-dimension scores + overall pass/fail           |
| **reprioritise**                 | read-write | User invokes reprioritise skill                                     | Prioritised project list; ≥10 Ready; actions taken |

### Key boundaries to avoid confusion

**investigator vs debugger:** Both are read-write bug hunters. Difference:

- **investigator** — parallelisable, dispatched per failure cluster when `gate:full` fails, no task-graph overhead (no `tg start`/`tg done`), reports back to orchestrator
- **debugger** — single task in the task graph (`tg start` → 4 phases → `tg done`), 3-attempt limit, escalates via `tg note`

**investigator vs reviewer (research):** Opposite permissions and purpose:

- **investigator** — read-write, fixes things, dispatched after failures
- **reviewer (research)** — read-only, gathers findings only, dispatched before creating a plan

**reviewer vs spec-reviewer/quality-reviewer:** Scoping:

- **reviewer** — general single-stage review; use when the task is clear and you want one PASS/FAIL verdict
- **spec-reviewer + quality-reviewer** — two-stage: spec first, quality second; use when you want explicit separation of "did it do what it was asked" vs "is the code good"

**Assessment specialists** (adversarial-security, risk-preparedness, factuality-traceability, fairness-equity, rubric-driven): Read-only specialists for security, change-level risk scorecard, factuality/docs consistency, process fairness, and rubric-based evaluation. Dispatched by the review skill or on demand when scope matches. See [reports/26-03-02_assessment_specialists_proposal.md](reports/26-03-02_assessment_specialists_proposal.md).

**fixer vs implementer:** Escalation ladder:

- **implementer** — first attempt at a task (fast model)
- **fixer** — escalation after 2 implementer failures (inherits session model = Sonnet/Opus); amends existing changes rather than redoing

